All classes live in com.academy.student, which allows the files/classes to references without imports.
A single Scanner object is created in main, passed to StudentManager's constructor to ensure proper use of 1 singular scanner at a time.
I also read whole lines and parse with Integer.parseInt instead of using nextInt() to avoid leftover newline bugs.
Every loop runs until studentCount, which was related to the an issue I encountered when in development, I had to double check my bounds didn't include the last (out of bounds) digit.


REFLECTION QUESTIONS

Why must the package folder tree match package com.academy.student?
Why prefer nextLine() + parse over nextInt() in a menu app?
Why keep a studentCount instead of relying on students.length alone?
What belongs in Main versus StudentManager?
How does this console CRUD prepare you for later Spring/customer labs without implementing them here?


1. Classloader and compiler need to identify the correct location of the code.
2. nextInt() leaves newline space in the buffer, this requires the user to press enter a second time when they do not know. Also good input validation.
3. Student.length() does not represent the amount of students the array holds. Only tells the total capacity, it would be inefficient.
4. Main is for running the high level program, keeping business logic separate. StudentManager is the business logic, all custom operations held personally by this class.
5. Shows a lot of behind the scenes validation, mechanisms that sometimes get abstracted away. Shows framework of architecture/logic behind adding and displaying objects.
    Shows simplified purpose behind different logic layers such as dto, api, service, db.
